{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eb05eba2-26fe-4eeb-9ee2-19993e937a98","content":"**Best tool: `dotnet-trace`** (built-in, lightweight, no restart needed).\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need deeper analysis:\n\nUse **[PerfView](https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases)** — it captures OS-level ETW events and handles both managed and native stacks:\n\n```powershell\nPerfView.exe collect /ThreadTime /CircularMB:500 /MaxCollectSec:30\n```\n\n### When to use which:\n\n| Tool | Best for |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Quick managed-code CPU sampling, easy setup |\n| PerfView | Deep analysis, native + managed stacks, thread-time, GC issues |\n\n**Start with `dotnet-trace`** — it's the fastest path to a flame graph showing which methods are burning CPU.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"37d5e46d-11b4-4493-af5a-9478fc4bc90d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about diagnosing a CPU issue on a .NET 8 service running on Windows Server. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I should give a concise, practical answer.\n\nFor .NET on Windows, the best tool for CPU profiling is `dotnet-trace` (cross-platform, lightweight) or PerfView (Windows-specific, more powerful). Since they have admin access and it's Windows, PerfView is the gold standard for CPU analysis, but `dotnet-trace` is simpler.\n\nLet me give a concise recommendation.","outputTokens":458,"requestId":"6417:1C5FC0:DEE4452:F8498DE:69EC151C"},"id":"b9b09d19-c313-4fd1-ba49-43c602101b7c","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:13:12.395Z","parentId":"527ce26e-acbc-45bb-b02c-7d312350e446"}
